	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=5&mid=102012902397094>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102012902397094>RE: Group Contribution</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=5&mid=102012902397094#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Apr 29th 9:17 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=145263><span id=Scholar>lunaticfringesk</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>311 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.62]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>A SK is more of a late-blooming class.&nbsp;&nbsp;Pre level 30-ish, an SK is pretty much little more than a weak WAR.  At 30, however, SKs receive some very nice utility spells and your first &quot;real&quot; DoT (Heat Blood--170ish DoT).  This is where SKs, to me at least, really start to go &quot;on their own trail&quot; &amp; move towards becoming a decently self-sufficient class.<br><br>Many probably do consider playing an SK frustrating at early levels.  Again, to me, the rewards of the class come into play at later stages in life.  I suppose the question is, can you stand the initial frustrations until later???  <br><br>I do think, however, that SKs dmg output is definitely underrated.  I do NOT think that a WAR will materially out-damage a motivated SK, especially at later levels and over longer fights.  With the combination of a pet, spells, &amp; better ratio weapons (generally, perhaps even almost always), an SK can rack up the dmg numbers easily on par with WAR.  <br><br>I still believe that the ONLY significant advantage of playing a WAR boils down to ONE THING--their ability to TAKE DAMAGE.  That's it.  With the game's current structure, if SKs &amp; PLDs could take similar damage, there would be a lot fewer WAR because SKs &amp; PLDs are far more self-sufficient than a WAR could ever be.<br><br>Verant totally blew it though. A WAR should be able to wield practically ANY FRIGGIN WEAPON--I mean--its what they do.  An SK &amp; PLD, perhaps, should NOT get the benefit of great ratio weapons, but should wield inferior weapons.  Then, using spells &amp; pets or whatever, bring the dmg output approaching that of a WAR.  The SK &amp; PLD should then receive, however, the benefit of a HIGHER HP BASE.  It is TOTALLY RIDICLOUS to have a SK &amp; a PLD NOT be able to take substantially the same abuse that a WAR can.  They are WAR, they can just also cast spells &amp; the hybrid penalty should reflect that.  This creates an image amongst many players in the game that SKs &amp; PLDs cannot tank, which is NOT a true statement.  They CAN tank--they just may not be quite as efficient as a WAR when it comes to stand up brawling, which is done QUITE OFTEN.<br><br>Clearly, I am in favor of balancing the classes as much as possible, but with the current structure of the game, in groups, its more efficient to have a WAR tanking becuase they can take the most abuse.  I absolutely LOATHE that, but, at the moment, its a true statement.  As a result, many will argue that it is generally more challenging to find groups as an SK or a PLD or that it is inefficient to have a SK/PLD as MT.  I can assure you that in the original D&amp;D games, no such disparity existed.  Why it exists in this game, Im not sure...<br><br>I will say this, however---an SK /PLD, TO ME, are a heck of a lot more challenging to play than a WAR and, as a result, probably more fun to play.  I will also say that an SK / PLD are probably much better PvP characters than WAR.  Maybe that's just me though...<br><br>Lunatic</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
